WEBVTT

00:09.260 --> 00:13.220
Coming up next is the science fiction radio show, so stay with us.

00:28.960 --> 00:34.320
This is the science fiction radio show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.880 --> 00:38.660
And here are your hosts.

00:42.680 --> 00:44.840
This is Daryl Lane and David Cruz.

00:45.280 --> 00:48.840
Poole Anderson is one of a small group of science fiction authors who have written future histories.

00:49.300 --> 00:53.460
A future history is a group of stories or novels written along a consistent timeline

00:53.460 --> 00:54.140
in the future.

00:54.680 --> 00:58.900
Characters may or may not recur, but the intention is to speculate on the evolution

00:58.900 --> 01:01.240
of human society beyond the present day.

01:01.620 --> 01:03.700
Anderson actually has written two future histories.

01:03.700 --> 01:07.300
The first is not as best known, and it consists of only a dozen or so stories.

01:07.780 --> 01:10.160
Anderson began it in the late 1940s.

01:10.280 --> 01:21.460
But I started out originally rather early in my career and more or less inspired by

01:21.460 --> 01:36.440
Heinlein's future history and constructed one of my own with charts and background material

01:36.440 --> 01:38.220
and so on, like his.

01:38.220 --> 01:47.080
Of course mine was in mind the events were different, but basically I wanted to do a

01:47.080 --> 02:01.320
similar job that is fictionally tell about the story of mankind from almost the present

02:01.320 --> 02:09.700
day up at least until the early year of expansion among the stars.

02:10.900 --> 02:16.580
This wasn't going to be the only thing I did by any means, although I would write other

02:16.580 --> 02:18.180
things that were not in the series.

02:20.320 --> 02:26.100
But from time to time I'd add something to it, and I did over the years.

02:33.140 --> 02:38.180
Some of the stories in this future history are Wolf, Quixote in the Windmill, Cold Victory,

02:38.760 --> 02:40.140
and The Snows of Ganymede.

02:40.580 --> 02:44.980
The earliest stories in the series describe World War 3, which Anderson had said in 1958,

02:45.480 --> 02:47.200
a war that destroys modern civilization.

02:47.740 --> 02:50.480
But out of the war decades later rose a new civilization.

02:50.980 --> 02:55.920
It was a repressive one dominated by the Psycho-Technic Institute, an organization which

02:55.920 --> 03:00.360
strictly plans and controls human progress through psychological manipulation.

03:00.920 --> 03:05.160
Anderson carefully traces out the social, political, and technological events which

03:05.160 --> 03:06.100
shape the new society.

03:06.500 --> 03:10.700
He describes the colonization of Venus and Mars, for instance, the development of robotics

03:10.700 --> 03:14.340
and artificial regeneration, and the struggle toward a true world government.

03:15.040 --> 03:19.340
In one story, The Troublemakers, he sends a space ark off to Alpha Centauri in a voyage that will

03:19.340 --> 03:20.800
take 123 years.

03:21.200 --> 03:26.180
But overall things don't go smoothly. Anderson envisions society undergoing many upheavals.

03:26.600 --> 03:30.020
In Quixote in the Windmill, for instance, there are violent anti-robot riots.

03:30.360 --> 03:34.620
And in Cold Victory, a humanist revolution occurs which overthrows the Psycho-Technic Institute.

03:34.980 --> 03:38.860
But some of the institute's people escape to Ganymede, the largest of Jupiter's moons,

03:39.000 --> 03:40.060
where they continue fighting.

03:40.800 --> 03:44.620
It isn't until the story break, the last one in this particular future history,

03:44.800 --> 03:46.380
that the institute is totally wiped out.

03:47.060 --> 03:51.660
At this point, around the 23rd century, the human race is ready to attempt interstellar colonization.

03:52.080 --> 03:54.320
Anderson leaves it there at the beginning of a new era.

03:54.620 --> 03:56.700
He explains why he added no more to it.

03:57.480 --> 04:00.440
But gradually, for a number of reasons,

04:02.240 --> 04:08.600
got less and less interested in continuing and started phasing it out, doing less and less of it.

04:09.240 --> 04:18.020
One reason for being less interested was that, as for the early part of it, reality was catching up with me.

04:18.820 --> 04:28.900
Not only were public or political events not working out on my timetable,

04:29.620 --> 04:37.780
for example, World War III did not come off on schedule, but also it turned out I had failed

04:37.780 --> 04:42.420
to foresee a number of scientific and technological developments.

04:43.600 --> 04:46.580
Anderson's second future history is much larger and better known.

04:46.580 --> 04:49.560
It includes some of the most memorable characters he's created,

04:50.040 --> 04:51.880
like Nicholas von Rine and Dominic Flandry.

04:52.200 --> 04:54.620
We'll talk with Anderson about that series next time.

