06:12.080 --> 06:17.440
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:20.140 --> 06:21.820
And here are your hosts.

06:26.380 --> 06:28.540
This is David Cruz and Daryl Lane.

06:29.040 --> 06:32.500
Poole Anderson has written one of the most ambitious and extensive future histories

06:32.500 --> 06:33.420
in science fiction.

06:33.780 --> 06:36.460
It's usually called the Future History of the Polysoteknic League,

06:36.780 --> 06:38.880
although a better term might be the League and Empire series.

06:39.260 --> 06:41.500
We asked Anderson how the future history got its start.

06:42.580 --> 06:47.140
Now that has a history much more like that of Tuipsy. It just grew.

06:50.820 --> 06:57.680
I've written a few stories about Nicholas von Rine and a few stories about Dominic Flandry,

06:57.780 --> 07:00.380
who lived in completely different miliaries, of course.

07:01.660 --> 07:10.460
And then one day on an impulse, I thought, well, gosh, they could be on the same timeline,

07:10.720 --> 07:13.180
one living about 500 years after the other.

07:14.160 --> 07:19.140
And through an invention of that in one of the once one of the Flandry stories,

07:21.300 --> 07:28.140
and then started fitting in other stories wherever it was convenient.

07:28.700 --> 07:36.240
You see, the thing with the future history is that although each story should, of course,

07:37.440 --> 07:43.160
be readable independently of any others and comprehensible and so on,

07:43.960 --> 07:51.280
nevertheless, if you have a reader who remembers a number of them, the cross connections will

07:51.280 --> 07:55.400
add an extra dimension and thereby a hope that's in his enjoyment.

07:58.420 --> 08:07.200
So I started doing it that way. And after a while realized I had a rather large beast by

08:07.200 --> 08:16.260
the tail. If I was going to stay consistent at all, then I had to keep careful notes.

08:17.080 --> 08:21.800
And I had to develop a systematic scheme and so on.

08:22.840 --> 08:28.140
And that's over the years one thing led to another until it all became

08:29.160 --> 08:39.760
rather elaborate. By now it includes, no, I think something like 40 separate items of which

08:41.200 --> 08:47.380
probably at least a third or so are full dressed novels.

08:48.580 --> 08:52.600
The first story Nicholas Von Ryn turned up in was the novel The Man Who Counts,

08:52.780 --> 08:58.100
which was also issued as the War of the Wingman. Von Ryn is a nonheroic type. He's a fat, loud

08:58.100 --> 09:03.660
mouthed, cursing schemer who favors good food, drink and creature comforts. But using his wits,

09:03.820 --> 09:08.960
he usually conquers all of his foes, human or alien. He establishes the Polysottechnic League,

09:09.260 --> 09:13.440
a trading guild which carries earth culture throughout the stars. We asked Anderson if Von Ryn

09:13.440 --> 09:21.080
has been popular with readers. Oh yes, there are some readers who can't stand him but they

09:22.300 --> 09:31.620
don't ignore him either and as for the rest, he probably is the most popular character I've

09:31.620 --> 09:37.420
ever come up with. Then about 500 years along the timeline of his future history, Anderson

09:37.420 --> 09:42.180
introduces Dominic Flandry, an agent for the Tarran Empire. He turns up in books like Ensign

09:42.180 --> 09:48.300
Flandry, The Rebel Worlds, Earthman Go Home, and A Night of Ghosts and Shadows. The Flandry stories

09:48.300 --> 09:52.420
are set in the 31st century and involve the Tarran Empire's druggler with its powerful alien

09:52.420 --> 09:58.580
antagonist, the Merseans. Flandry is the opposite of Von Ryn. He smooths, sophisticated, suave,

09:58.940 --> 10:03.880
a man who can either fight or scheme with equal style and flair. He reminds a reader of James Bond.

10:04.320 --> 10:10.840
We asked Anderson if the relationship was intentional. Oh no, nor did I ask this before and

10:10.840 --> 10:15.640
as a matter of fact, the first Flandry story appeared something like 20 years before the first

10:15.640 --> 10:23.760
James Bond story did. If I was modeling on any other character at all, it would probably have

10:23.760 --> 10:29.240
had to be somebody like the sink. Anderson says he probably won't be adding any more to the future

10:29.240 --> 10:34.000
history of the Polysoteknic League and the Tarran Empire, but there's enough material there already

10:34.000 --> 10:39.120
to keep a science fiction reader busy for a long time. We'll have some more on Poole Anderson next time.

