12:10.200 --> 12:14.960
This is Daryl Lane and David Cruz. A number of science fiction authors employ the technique

12:14.960 --> 12:19.580
of worldbuilding in their stories. Poole Anderson is one of the best at worldbuilding. He explains the

12:19.580 --> 12:33.320
term. The term simply refers to the construction of an imaginary world as a setting for a story

12:33.980 --> 12:43.400
in considerable detail. Now, lots of people have done this. An obvious example, for example,

12:43.700 --> 12:54.660
would be J.R.R. Tolkien in The Lord of the Rings and Related Stories. He constructs an imaginary

12:54.660 --> 13:01.940
world in vast detail, complete down the fine points of the various languages spoken and so on.

13:02.800 --> 13:06.180
Anderson's first extensive attempt at worldbuilding was the Planet Diomedes,

13:06.400 --> 13:10.220
which was a setting for his novel The Man Who Counts. He meticulously constructs the

13:10.220 --> 13:15.200
planet in detail that allows winged intelligent beings. The atmosphere, for example, is very

13:15.200 --> 13:20.260
heavy, which is necessary to support a large flying creature. Anderson explains why he spends

13:20.260 --> 13:23.340
so much time constructing his planets in consistent and careful detail.

13:24.260 --> 13:33.340
After all, we really cannot reasonably expect that any other planet anywhere in the universe

13:33.340 --> 13:41.400
will be very much like Earth. We'll probably be lucky if we find a few where humans can live

13:41.400 --> 13:51.460
without artificial help. And you're certainly not going to have native humans around there

13:52.420 --> 14:00.780
or oak trees or rabbits or any other feature that we know here on Earth.

14:03.300 --> 14:09.560
That's just preposterous, to suppose, on the basis of everything we know about the evolution of life

14:09.560 --> 14:22.120
here on Earth. So, in that case, let's try to set up some of the features which are different.

14:23.880 --> 14:31.500
After all, one reason people read science fiction is precisely that they like to get away from the

14:31.500 --> 14:38.100
world around them once in a while and escape into something exotic. In my opinion,

14:40.120 --> 14:47.800
to the extent that this exotic thing can be made at the same time realistic and convincing,

14:48.760 --> 14:51.220
the reader is getting his money's worth.

14:57.740 --> 15:02.220
Almost any world constructed by Anderson in his science fiction stories is put together with

15:02.220 --> 15:06.800
attention given to basic scientific laws. Anderson, after all, was a physics student in

15:06.800 --> 15:12.020
college and knows his science. Other authors, Hal Clement and Larry Niven come to mind, practice

15:12.020 --> 15:16.700
careful world building too. In fact, Clement says his science fiction novel challenges its readers

15:16.700 --> 15:21.460
to find any scientific errors committed by the author. Clement calls this The Game. Anderson

15:21.460 --> 15:30.700
elaborates on it. The game consists in an author setting up a world or a situation or something

15:30.700 --> 15:35.400
the very best he can and writing a story about it.

15:37.240 --> 15:46.280
And then that's all he can do. He's made his move and that's it. And readers are free to

15:47.280 --> 15:55.140
thereafter to try to figure out from the story exactly what he had in mind and exactly where he

15:55.140 --> 16:04.220
may have gone wrong. So I've gotten some very interesting mail on technical points. And yes,

16:04.480 --> 16:12.540
sometimes they have indicated to me that I've goofed on this or that detail, but all right.

16:13.500 --> 16:18.360
Wondering from that, I don't mind. With Anderson and with other world builders,

16:18.840 --> 16:22.760
a reader gets a bonus to accompany an exciting narrative, interesting and accurate science.

16:23.480 --> 16:25.600
More with Poole Anderson in our next show.

