17:56.360 --> 18:02.120
This is David Cruz and Daryl Lane. Poole Anderson is noted both as a master world builder and as a

18:02.120 --> 18:07.080
creator of believable aliens. He matches aliens to their planets with meticulous and loving care

18:07.080 --> 18:12.060
and with great concern for scientific accuracy. One of the best examples of his talents in this area

18:12.060 --> 18:16.640
is the race of winged creatures included in his future history of the Polysotheknic League.

18:17.300 --> 18:20.060
Actually, he constructed two separate races of winged beings,

18:20.560 --> 18:24.940
the Diomedians from the Nicholas Von Ryn novel The Man Who Counts and the Ythrians of the planet

18:24.940 --> 18:30.140
Avalon. Anderson explains how he got interested in intelligent beings with the ability to fly.

18:30.860 --> 18:37.360
All the way back when, many years ago, I mean many years ago,

18:39.340 --> 18:46.840
it's about 40 by now, Elsprake the Camp had published an article on

18:48.040 --> 18:59.600
intelligent non-human beings. He used basic physical principles to demolish a number of notions,

18:59.760 --> 19:05.740
you know, like the idea of a giant insect and so on. It's just impossible. It would collapse

19:05.740 --> 19:11.000
under its own weight because it hasn't got the structure to support that weight, things like that.

19:12.400 --> 19:18.960
And one thing he doubted was that you could have an intelligent being which flies

19:22.300 --> 19:38.380
because the wing loading that a living flyer can absorb is or take

19:38.380 --> 19:44.820
is so small that there just wouldn't be room for a sizable brain.

19:46.220 --> 19:50.380
Anderson thought about the camp's arguments and at last came to at least a partial solution.

19:51.540 --> 19:55.700
Well, science fiction writers tend to take this sort of a thing as a challenge.

19:57.760 --> 20:01.120
And so when I wrote The Man Who Counts quite a while ago,

20:04.520 --> 20:11.120
I did have wing intelligent beings, but I designed a planet such that it had a very dense atmosphere

20:13.340 --> 20:16.500
which of course would make it easier to get about in the air.

20:18.820 --> 20:24.960
I also made them essentially six-limbed so that they could have not only wings but

20:24.960 --> 20:32.080
legs and hands. Well, after what I got to thinking that that had been a kind of a cop-out,

20:32.300 --> 20:39.160
couldn't there be some way to do it better? Could it conceivably be done on an earth-like planet?

20:39.760 --> 20:46.060
I couldn't see any way. The camp's arguments were there and they made sense.

20:47.480 --> 20:51.640
At this point, the famous science fiction editor, John W. Campbell, came to the rescue.

20:52.460 --> 20:59.000
Well, when it happened, the very last time I saw the late John W. Campbell,

21:00.580 --> 21:06.920
we, I was in New York and visited his office and we went out to lunch together.

21:08.400 --> 21:12.860
This was not long before his death and we sat there talking.

21:14.220 --> 21:17.940
And during their conversation, Anderson brought up the problem of constructing a large intelligent

21:17.940 --> 21:21.080
creature who could fly. Campbell suggested a way to do it.

21:22.240 --> 21:26.500
And he immediately said, well, suppose it had some sort of leg-driven

21:30.180 --> 21:33.580
supercharging bellows that would give a tremendous curse of ability.

21:36.580 --> 21:46.000
And I immediately saw that this was a way to power a winged animal, give it sufficient energy that

21:46.560 --> 21:50.180
it actually could fly in an atmosphere like our own.

21:52.720 --> 21:55.480
Although it might weigh as much as 100 tons.

21:56.140 --> 21:59.440
So on this hint, Anderson created the Ithrians of the planet Avalon.

21:59.880 --> 22:04.100
The people of the wind is probably the best known of his novels involving the Ithrians,

22:04.500 --> 22:08.480
but Anderson used them in a number of stories in his Polycystoknecht League Future History.

22:09.340 --> 22:11.240
Next time, we'll have more with Poole Anderson.

